1. Dramatic decline in job satisfaction

The data

The cities-job-satisfaction.csv dataset contains (fictional) data from different cities around the world. In this data it was measured which proportion of people reported that they were unsatisfied with their work situation this year compared to last year. Each data point is a different city, and the value indicates the proportion of dissatisfied workers.

My plot

ggplot

My claim

You can clearly see in this plot that people are dramatically more dissatisfied at work this year compared to last year. I have used transparency for the dots to prevent overplotting/oversaturation, so this means that the entire dark area has an even amount of cities throughout. In other words, there are as many cities that increased from ~0% to ~40% dissatisfaction as there are cities that stayed around 0%. That's atrocious!

Question 1.1

rubric={reasoning:2,writing:1}

  • Explain which mistakes (if any) I have done in my plot and provide an interpretation of the data that is more correct than mine. Be brief and clear in your answer.
  • You might have some ideas just from looking at my plot, but you will likely need to do some investigation yourself to answer this question fully. You can reference your improved plot as needed.

The plot is misleading because heavy overplotting plus transparency creates a very dark blob, but darkness does not mean the points are evenly distributed across that region. The darkness mainly shows that many cities are concentrated near low last_year dissatisfaction, not that all changes are equally common. Also, interpreting an increase requires comparing to the y = x line (no change). From the scatter, most cities appear to have similar or slightly higher dissatisfaction this year, but the biggest pattern is that many cities were already low last year and remain relatively low, with a smaller number showing larger increases.

# YOUR ANSWER HERE
library(readr)
library(ggplot2)

df <- read_csv("data/cities-job-satisfaction.csv", show_col_types = FALSE)

# If hexbin is not installed yet, run:
# install.packages("hexbin")
library(hexbin)

ggplot(df, aes(x = last_year, y = this_year)) +
  # Use hex bins to show density (fix overplotting)
  geom_hex(bins = 35) +
  # Reference line: no change (this_year = last_year)
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", linewidth = 0.8, color = "white") +
  coord_fixed(xlim = c(0, 1), ylim = c(0, 1), expand = FALSE) +
  labs(
    title = "Job dissatisfaction: this year vs last year (cities)",
    subtitle = "Colour shows how many cities fall in each area; dashed line indicates no change (y = x)",
    x = "Dissatisfied proportion (last year)",
    y = "Dissatisfied proportion (this year)",
    fill = "City count"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
    legend.position = "right"
  )

2. I will keep raising wages for all

The data

The wages.csv dataset contains (fictional) data from different companies in the city where I have been the mayor for the last few years. Each datapoint represents the average salary at a company. All the major companies in this city were surveyed both before I was elected and after a few years of my governing. However, this is not paired data, some companies are different from "before" and "after", so you do not need to do a paired analysis.

My plots

ggplot

My claim

As you can see, I have been able to produce a significant increase in the average salary for workers in my city. This high raise almost certainly entails that all (or almost all) workers are receiving a higher payment than what they were before I started to govern. But since I know you are going to ask me for more robust estimates, I have also provided the median increase (which is even more notable) and the number of workers in each group (so that you can see that the samples are balanced).

Question 2.1

rubric={reasoning:2,writing:1}

  • Explain which mistakes (if any) I have done in my plot and provide an interpretation of the data that is more correct than mine. Be brief and clear in your answer.
  • You might have some ideas just from looking at my plot, but you will likely need to do some investigation yourself to answer this question fully. You can reference your improved plot as needed.

These plots are misleading because they only show group summaries (mean/median) and hide the full distributions. A higher mean/median after does not prove that (almost) everyone earns more, since outliers or a few high-salary companies can raise the average while many companies stay the same or drop. Also, the data are not paired, so we cannot claim the same companies increased. A more correct interpretation is: salaries are generally higher on average after, but we cannot conclude that nearly all workers benefited without showing the distributions and overlap.

wages <- read_csv("data/wages.csv", show_col_types = FALSE)

wages <- wages %>%

  group_by(when) %>%

  geom_col(width = 0.9) +

# YOUR ANSWER HERE
library(readr)
library(ggplot2)

wages <- read_csv("data/wages.csv", show_col_types = FALSE)

ggplot(wages, aes(x = when, y = salary, fill = when)) +
  geom_violin(trim = FALSE, alpha = 0.35, color = NA) +
  geom_boxplot(width = 0.18, outlier.shape = NA, alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.08, alpha = 0.35, size = 1.6) +
  labs(
    title = "Company wages: before vs after (distribution)",
    subtitle = "Violin/box shows spread; points show individual companies",
    x = NULL,
    y = "Salary"
  ) +
  theme_grey(base_size = 12) +
  theme(
    legend.position = "none",
    aspect.ratio = 0.6
  )

3. Guns to the people

The data

The guns-r-us.csv dataset contains yearly data for the number of murders by firearms in Florida.

My plots

ggplot

My claim

As you can see, just after the gun law in Florida was enacted, deaths from firearms plummeted. I don't really think there is much else to discuss here.

Question 3.1

rubric={reasoning:2,writing:1}

  • Explain which mistakes (if any) I have done in my plot and provide an interpretation of the data that is more correct than mine. Be brief and clear in your answer.
  • You might have some ideas just from looking at my plot, but you will likely need to do some investigation yourself to answer this question fully. You can reference your improved plot as needed.

This plot suggests the gun law caused murders to drop, but the data only shows a before/after time trend, so it cannot prove causation. There is no control group, and murders already fluctuate over time. The design (big red background + annotation) pushes the viewer toward one conclusion. A more accurate interpretation is: firearm murders change over time, and there is a decrease after the law, but we cannot say the law caused it.

My approval ratings are astronomical

The data

The (fictional) state-comparison.csv dataset contains a sample of voters from my state and a neighboring state of similar socioeconomic standard. Voters in each state were asked to rate their approval of the state's mayor on a scale from 0 - 10,000.

My plots

ggplot

My claim

My approval ratings are through the roof! I am clearly doing a better job than my colleague and competitor next doors. And as you can see we sampled enough people to get smooth curves, which means that this difference is both likely to be statistically significant and the magnitude is just too big to ignore. There seems to be a few bores on the lower end of the spectrum, but can't win them all I guess. Do you want a 10k approval rating future?

Question 4.1

rubric={reasoning:2,writing:1}

  • Explain which mistakes (if any) I have done in my plot and provide an interpretation of the data that is more correct than mine. Be brief and clear in your answer.
  • You might have some ideas just from looking at my plot, but you will likely need to do some investigation yourself to answer this question fully. You can reference your improved plot as needed.

This plot is misleading because the KDE waves hide the raw data and sample size, so the smooth curves do not prove that the difference is real or statistically significant. Also, using filled overlapping densities makes comparison harder and can exaggerate the separation. Finally, the 010,000 scale and the vague x-axis label (the value) reduce interpretability.

A more accurate interpretation is that the two states approval distributions overlap a lot: one state appears to have more very high ratings, but many voters in both states give similar ratings. To support the claim, we would need to show the number of voters and add clearer summaries/uncertainty (e.g., median/IQR, confidence bands, or raw points).

# YOUR ANSWER TO #2 GOES HERE
library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(scales)

url <- "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/UofTCoders/workshops-dc-py/master/data/processed/world-data-gapminder.csv"
gap <- read_csv(url, show_col_types = FALSE)

df_2007 <- gap %>%
  filter(year == 2007) %>%
  arrange(desc(population)) 

ggplot(df_2007, aes(x = income, y = life_expectancy, size = population, fill = region)) +
  geom_point(shape = 21, color = "white", alpha = 0.80, stroke = 0.25) +
  scale_x_log10(
    labels = dollar_format(prefix = "$"),
    breaks = c(500, 2000, 10000, 50000)
  ) +
  scale_size_area(
    max_size = 14,
    breaks = c(5e6, 5e7, 5e8, 1e9),
    labels = label_number(scale_cut = cut_si(""))
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Life expectancy vs income (2007)",
    subtitle = "Bubble size = population; color = region",
    x = "Income (log scale)",
    y = "Life expectancy (years)",
    fill = "Region",
    size = "Population",
    caption = "Data: world-data-gapminder.csv"
  ) +
  guides(
    # NEW parameter: make legend symbols easier to read
    size = guide_legend(override.aes = list(alpha = 1)),
    fill = guide_legend(override.aes = list(alpha = 1, size = 5))
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(
    plot.title.position = "plot",
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    legend.position = "right"
  )

YOU ANSWER TO #3 GOES HERE

I improved communication by using a log scale for income, adding a clear title/subtitle and readable axis labels, and using meaningful population size breaks so the bubble sizes are interpretable. I also reduced overplotting by setting transparency and drawing larger countries first.

New parameter (not discussed in lectures): guide_legend(override.aes = ...). I used it to make the legend symbols easier to read (full opacity and clearer markers), so the chart is more suitable for communication.
